Replit Agent Instructions: Fix Page Landing & Scroll Position (Detailed Breakdown)

A. General Goal

Streamlit currently loads or re-renders pages at inconsistent scroll positions.
I want predictable, intentional scroll behaviour, based on the user’s action.

B. Required Behaviour

When a card, button, or navigation element loads a new section the page must always scroll to the very top (scroll position = 0).

Explicit implementation steps

The agent must:

Inject JavaScript that forces scroll to top on navigation:

window.scrollTo(0, 0);

Trigger that JS:

after any card click

after page state changes that represent navigation

Disable Streamlit’s “retain scroll position” behaviour.

Apply JS on page load to override Streamlit’s default.

Expected result

Whenever a user clicks a card or navigates to a new section, the viewport always resets to the top of the page.

-------------------------------

C. Required Behaviour

When the chat updates, the UI must always scroll to the bottom of the chat container, where the latest exchange is.

Explicit implementation steps

The agent must:

Wrap the chat messages in a scrollable container with a unique HTML ID.
Example:

<div id="chat-container"> ...messages... </div>


Inject JavaScript that scrolls this container to its bottom:

var chatBox = document.getElementById("chat-container");
chatBox.scrollTop = chatBox.scrollHeight;


Trigger this JS:

after each message is added

after Streamlit reruns due to user input

Ensure the chat input box remains visible (sticky bottom).

Expected result

When chatting, the user always sees the newest message and input box without needing to scroll manually.

-------------------------------

D. Putting Both Behaviours Together

To avoid confusion for the agent, spell out the logic:

If the user is navigating (card click / switching page):

➡️ Scroll to top of page (scrollY = 0)

If the user is chatting (sending/receiving messages):

➡️ Scroll to bottom of chat container

The agent must treat these as two separate scroll rules triggered by different UI actions.

-------------------------------

E. Use st.session_state to differentiate:

session_state["mode"] = "navigation"

session_state["mode"] = "chat"

Run JS conditionally based on mode.

This improves reliability.

